<h2>East Pasco climate and AC sizing — why it matters</h2>
<p>Zephyrhills sits inland at slightly higher elevation than coastal Tampa Bay communities, and the afternoon sea breeze arrives later here with less cooling effect. The design temperature for east Pasco County — used to properly size replacement HVAC equipment — is approximately 93°F dry-bulb with 76°F wet-bulb. This is meaningfully different from the 91–92°F design day used for Tampa coastal areas. A contractor who uses the wrong design temperature will undersize your replacement system for Zephyrhills peak conditions. We use location-specific Manual-J calculations for every replacement we quote here — not a tonnage-per-square-foot rule of thumb.</p>

<h2>Heating in Zephyrhills — freeze protection matters</h2>
<p>Zephyrhills has historically seen slightly more frequent below-freezing events than Tampa's coastal areas. Heat pump owners should have their system's defrost cycle tested annually — a defrost cycle that isn't functioning will cause ice buildup on the outdoor coil during cold snaps and switch the system to emergency heat, significantly increasing your electric bill. We test defrost cycles on every fall maintenance visit. Heat strip amp-draw verification is part of that test — failed heat strips silently spike bills during the 20–30 hours a year Zephyrhills sees sub-40°F temperatures.</p>

